In [[television]], a '''revival''' is a [[television program|television series]] that returns to produce new [[episode]]s after being off the air for a certain amount of time, particularly due to [[cancellation (television)|cancellation]].<ref name="V-Wagmeister">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/television-revival-series-heroes-coach-x-files-fuller-house-1201519079/|title=TV Revivals Making a Comeback: ‘Coach,’ ‘X-Files,’ ‘Fuller House’ & More|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=15 June 2015}}</ref> [[Television network|Network]] executives may decide to attempt to revive a [[television program]] when they feel that a [[Market (economics)|market]] once again exists for it. It is one of several programming strategies television networks employ to capitalize further on successful programs; among the other methods are [[Spin-off (media)|spin-offs]], [[Reboot (fiction)|reboots]], [[remakes]], [[Casting (performing arts)|cast]] reunions, and [[television film|television movies]].
Unlike spin-offs, in which a television network creates an entirely new series around an existing [[Fictional character|character]], a revival reintroduces most or many of the original program's [[Plot (narrative)|storylines]], characters, and locales. Revivals usually take place at some point after the original series ends. By contrast, [[Reboot (fiction)|reboots]] and [[remake]]s may feature many of the original characters, but are usually played by new cast members and without taking into account events or [[Continuity (fiction)|continuity]] that occurred during the original series.<ref>http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/driving-resurgence-reboots-remakes-revivals-tv-film/story?id=47645549</ref>
